report narrative: In the European Union and Germany, extensive quantities of cheese were delivered a few days before the past holiday. Therefore, current stocks of cheese are at very low levels and insufficient to satisfy any unplanned requests. It is expected that sales will remain lively in January since customers have actively started to book their orders for that month. Current cheese prices continue to be lower. Cheese production is steady, in line with seasonal expectations. A slight boost in prices has been noted for January deliveries. In additional, the present dynamic export sales are likely to further stimulate the increase in prices. In the US, the wholesale prices for domestic foreign type cheese are trending higher by $0.0450 compared to last week, whereas the price for domestic Swiss cheese and import varieties are unchanged from a week ago.

report narrative: Cheese sales in Germany and in other European Union (EU) countries are lively in view of year-end holidays. Buying interest from all sale channels is rising and they are expected to continue to enlarge until the holidays. Worldwide market requests for EU cheese are within the usual figure compared to past years. Current low stocks are barely enough to meet the growing demand. Altogether, cheese prices have recently stabilized at rock-bottom levels, easing the competitiveness of EU cheese in the global market. Cheese yield has remained flat because of lower milk output in some of the EUs main milk producing countries. In the U.S., wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano cheese prices dropped $0.0025, but Swiss cheese prices moved up $.1275. All other prices stand still at the levels of the preceding week.

report narrative: In the European Union, the cheese market tone is stable. Cheese production is steady, following a similar trend to farm milk output. Cheese demand is active due to the approaching end of the year holidays. With increasing cheese sales, manufacturers supplies remain limited. In the domestic market, sliced cheese is available because many of the sale channels place early cheese orders to ensure that they wont run out of stocks. The food retail sector sales are growing as additional inquiries come in. Demand from the export market is outgoing, enhanced by the favorable euro exchange rate compared to the U.S. dollar and a reduction in cheese prices. Contacts notice a recent drop in hard cheese prices. In the U.S., the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano decreased by $0.0075, but all other prices are unchanged from a week ago.

report narrative: In the European Union, export sales diverge depending on the exporting country. In addition, the strong dollar, coupled with a weaker value of the Euro are giving European cheese processors a competitive edge over their adversaries. In Germany, the sliced cheese market continues to be tight. Orders for the holidays have started to increase, mainly in the domestic market. All available cheese stocks are being used by buyers. On average, inventories are still lower and insufficient to meet all demands. As the result, some delivery schedules had to be postponed to later dates or the quantities delivered are being reduced. Milk output in the big-three milk producing regions of Europe remains below the previous year level. As so, cheese production cannot be increased. In the U.S., the domestic prices for the top four foreign cheese types in the table below decreased $.0600, but all other prices are unchanged from last week.

In the U.S., the domestic prices for the top four foreign cheese types in the table below decreased $.0600, but all other prices are unchanged from last week.

report narrative: In the European Union (EU), the sliced cheese market is solid, characterized by inventories limited availability. The stocks are unlikely to recoup in the short-term. Because of lower milk output, the volumes of milk flowing to cheese manufacturing facilities cannot be increased. Cheese prices are primarily steady. However, some occasional short-term discounted prices have been noted for block cheese sales among EU countries. Overall, processors are pleased with the sales situation as orders from both big retailers and the industry are active. There is currently more seasonal demand for semi-hard cheese. Overall, cheese trade within the EU is at a normal level. In the U.S. the prices for domestically produced foreign-type cheese declined $.0750, whereas Swiss and imported cheese prices are unchanged from last week.

report narrative: In Germany, the sliced cheese market is balanced. Manufacturers are satisfied with current domestic sales. Exports of cheese to other European Union countries are stable. Although large volumes of cheese continue to flow to other countries, the competition level is stronger. The supplies of cheese are currently balanced to lower. There are some concerns that cheese provisions might not be enough in the coming weeks as cheese demand is expected to increase during the fall festivities while the future growth of cheese production is unpredictable. On one hand, the discussions for contractual cheese prices are strengthening. However, on the other hand, prices for block cheese are a bit mixed as current offers are made at lower prices. This week, the prices for domestically produced foreign-type cheese are down by $.0400, whereas Swiss and imported cheese prices are steady.

This week, the prices for domestically produced foreign-type cheese are down by $.0400, whereas Swiss and imported cheese prices are steady.
methodology: Information for the period October 15 - 19, 2018, issued weekly

report narrative: The German cheese market tone is steady. Global market orders as well as domestic orders are both stable and in line with usual requests for this season of the year. Cheese stocks, although enough to meet the needs of current buyers, are declining. In some instances, spot orders had to be postponed due to the young age structure of the inventories. As milk production decreases at levels lower than what was expected, cheese production remains steady to declining. The possibility of increasing cheese production is uncertain. Retail sale prices have increased noticeably. Nevertheless, prices for semi-hard cheese are generally firm. In the United States, wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano prices moved up $0.0350 while Swiss cheese prices decreased $.1225. The prices for all the other cheese types havent changed from a week ago.

report narrative: In Germany, sliced cheese sales are good this week. Domestic retail and wholesale orders are solid while international sales to other EU countries and to the rest of the world remain stable. Cheese production is unchanged from last week. Due to declining milk output, cheese processors are unable to adjust higher current cheese production volumes to match the needs of the industry. As so, cheese inventories are still lower and insufficient to meet short-term requests. Next month, milk production is expected to decrease while cheese demand will most likely increase. As a result, cheese supply is unlikely to improve soon. In Germany and in the EU, cheese prices are currently stable. In the United States, wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano prices moved up by $0.0400, but the prices of all other cheese types are unchanged from a week ago.

report narrative: Milk production in the European Union (EU) continues to bounce back from the latest drought, despite lower component levels reported. Cheese productivity is stable to growing as cheese makers receive more milk. Nevertheless, cheese prices are steady to somewhat declining. Cheese intakes both by the international and domestic markets are active. In Germany, domestic demand for sliced cheese is good. U.S. trade issues with some countries are creating an opportunity for the EU to supplies more cheese to those countries. Nonetheless, competition for international market shares is still tense. Cheese inventories in the EU remain in good balance with demand. However, In Germany, stocks for young age cheese are lower. In the United States of America, wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano prices increased $0.0075 whereas all other cheese prices stand still at the same level as last week.

report narrative: The European Union (EU) is characterized by a firm cheese market. As milk volumes are currently lower in the EU compared to a year ago, cheese production remains mainly steady from week to week. Spot trading activity is fairly stable. In the U.S., wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano prices decreased $0.0200. However, steadiness in prices has been noted for all the other cheese types.

report narrative: Recent heatwaves in some parts of the European Union have affected total farm milk output. As the result, cheese production has been steady to decreasing this week. Cheese sales to domestic and international customers have remained active. New cheese orders are coming from newly acquired market share, giving an extra boost to demand. However, the downside is that inventory levels are lower and cannot satisfy all short-term demand, somewhat limiting spot trading activities. The European Union cheese market undertone is currently firm. On the other hand, U.S. prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano dropped by $.0200 whereas all other U.S. cheese prices held steady compared to the previous week.

report narrative: In the European Union (EU), cheese trading is active. Demand from the domestic as well as the global market is robust. Due to U.S. trade issues with some countries, some of the buyers from those countries are turning to the EU to get the supplies of cheese they need. As the result, cheese stocks are further declining in the EU to the point where supplies are not enough to fulfill some immediate needs. Overall, cheese prices have remained firm. Last week, the EU and Japan signed a tariff-free trade agreement in which the EU cheese will enter Japan without any tariff. In addition, currently there are trade negotiations ongoing between the South American countries (Mercosur) and the EU that might affect the EU cheese market. report narrative: European Union(EU) cheese processing is strong, as additional milk volumes are clearing into cheese vats. The demand within the EU and from some international markets is stable and expanding as US trade policies are altered. The cheese prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano, in the U.S. decreased $.0050. However, Swiss prices and all other cheese prices are unchanged in comparison to last week.

Overall, export sales to southern European holiday countries are good. Exports to other countries are mostly steady. Sliced cheese stocks are just enough to meet current demand. They continue to be below the usual seasonal level. Cheese production is unchanged from last week. However, for the forthcoming months, the expected seasonal decline in milk volume is more likely to cause lower cheese output as milk powder and butter utilization increase. In the U.S., the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan Italy, and Romano decreased $.0125. All other prices are unchanged compared to last week.

report narrative: The European Union (EU) cheese market was strong in April and May, and it is showing the same tendency this month. Cheese sales within the EU and in the export market are good. The weaker exchange rate is contributing to a boost in international orders. Although cheese is currently among the most produced dairy products in the EU, stocks are at lower levels due to higher demand. In the first quarter of 2018, cheese output up-stretched by 1.8 percent. In general, EU cheese prices have soared for spot purchases. In the U.S., the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan Italy, and Romano curtailed $.0200, but Swiss cuts Switzerland prices increased $.0925. All other prices are unchanged compared to last week.

report narrative: The German semi-hard cheese market is firm. Cheese requests from all sale channels have remained high. Export sales to southern European holiday countries are good. Despite the instabilities resulting from public holidays, constantly higher loads of cheese have been delivered to buyers for the past weeks. Stocks for some types of cheese are below seasonal norms. Reports suggest that sellers are demanding higher prices in current hard cheese price negotiations. In the U.S., the weekly average block price on the CME moved up by $.0195, resulting in an increase in domestic foreign type cheese prices. However, domestic Swiss cut and imported cheese prices are unchanged from a week ago.

report narrative: As the European Union (EU) spring flush milk production increases, so does cheese production. Among all the dairy products, cheese is the foremost product being made. Hence, cheese is becoming more obtainable in the market. After a period of upsurge, EU cheese prices appear to be stabilizing. However, German cheese stocks have remained lower despite extensive cheese production in Germany. Not all requests can be met for spot demand. Retail orders abound. Exports of cheese from Germany to European holiday countries are seasonally up. In the U.S., the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan Italy, and Romano decreased $.0700. All other prices are unchanged compared to last week.

report narrative: In Germany, cheese production has remained at a higher level due to sufficient milk supplies available for processing. However, inventories for sliced cheese are currently lower. Most stocks have been contracted ahead of time. As so, spot loads are limited. German cheese export sales are lively. Demand from Southern Europe is increasing because of the holiday. Food retailers and large consumers are ordering quickly to secure the stocks they need. Some reports suggest that hard cheese sellers are requiring higher prices for the upcoming month and quarter contracts negotiations. In the U.S., the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan Italy, and Romano increased $.0225. All other prices are unchanged compared to last week.

report narrative: The European Union (EU) cheese market is currently firm. Most processors expect the market trend to stand still for a while. Although reports suggest extensive cheese output in Germany, strong sales coupled with limited cheese availability are keeping prices at a higher level. In 2016 and 2017, around the month of April up to the month of October, German cheese prices moved up. Therefore, market participants are wondering if this year, prices will follow the same trend as in 2016 and 2017. In Germany, higher prices have caused an abrupt cheese demand as buyers try to hedge their stocks before a further increase in prices. Sales of cheese within and outside the EU are currently very active. In the U.S., the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan Italy, and Romano increased $.0375, but Swiss cuts Switzerland prices decreased $.0675. all other prices are unchanged compared to last week.

Some orders are postponed to later dates, while the quantities delivered for other orders are reduced based on the supplies on hand. Cheese production is mostly tied to contractual obligations as producers focus on fulfilling those orders first. In current negotiations, sellers are demanding higher prices. In the United States, the prices for all cheese types are unchanged from the previous week.

report narrative: Cheese inventories in the European Union (EU) remain lower due to robust demand both in the domestic and export markets. Although semi-hard cheese, cheddar cheese, as well as other cheese types are selling strong in Germany, non-contractual cheese orders are challenging to fulfill. In general, prices for EU cheese have remained higher. However, reports suggest that German cheese items' prices have declined in the retail sector. Cheese production is currently ongoing and might increase in the coming weeks as the EU approaches the spring flush, which was delayed by adverse climatic conditions. In the United States, the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano augmented by $.0625. All other prices stayed still compared to a week ago.

report narrative: European Union (EU) cheese sales slowed down a little bit right after the holiday. However, they are showing signs of revival. In Germany, exports to Southern Europe and other countries continue to be solid. EU cheese supplies in storage are younger and still limited in quantities. Additional cheese requests can hardly be filled in the German dairy market. EU cheese production is active, supported by higher milk production trends. In the United States, the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano increased $.0200, but Swiss cuts Switzerland decreased $.1600. All other prices remained the same compared to the previous week.

In Germany, exports to Southern Europe and other countries continue to be solid. EU cheese supplies in storage are younger and still limited in quantities. Additional cheese requests can hardly be filled in the German dairy market. EU cheese production is active, supported by higher milk production trends. In the United States, the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano increased $.0200, but Swiss cuts Switzerland decreased $.1600. All other prices remained the same compared to the previous week.

report narrative: In the European Union (EU), cheese demand has been consistently higher and absorbed most of the available inventories. During the holiday weekend, additional demand for cheese could not be fulfilled due to limited availability. With the holiday being earlier this year, Southern Europe requests for EU cheese have revived unusually early. Cheese output is up in that abundant supplies of milk are present in the dairy market. The cheese price increase that started in mid-January, intensified in March. In general, the prices for mozzarella and cheddar raised. However, the surge in sliced cheese price has recently slowed down. In the United States, the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano slipped $.0225, while all other prices held constant compared to last week.

report narrative: In Germany, retailers and large consumers' cheese demand for the spring holiday continues to upsurge. Sales of Mozzarella cheese are particularly rising. Overall, cheese inventories remain insufficient to meet all needs. The current stocks of cheese have a younger age structure and are at persistently low levels. Holiday orders were planned ahead of time. Nonetheless, it is still a challenge to fulfill all the delivery requests. Sliced cheese prices have a higher tendency, lining up with recent contract negotiation values. In the European Union (EU), milk production is higher, resulting in active cheese yield. Cheese prices remain mixed within the EU. In the United States, the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano slipped $.0075, while all other prices held constant compared to last week.

Therefore, prices continue to increase. Stocks for immediate needs are limited. However, contracted loads are moving as planned. In the United States, the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, and Romano increased by $.0125 whereas all other prices held steady compared to last week.

methodology: Information for the period February 26 -  March 2, 2018, issued weekly

report narrative: In the European Union (EU), cheese production is ongoing following usual seasonal patterns. In general, cheese inventories are adequate to satisfy buyers' requests. However, in Germany, the availability of uncommitted cheese is limited. As so, sliced cheese offer prices are trending up in Germany. Reports also suggest that in Italy, the prices for hard cheese have dropped below that of the two prior years at the same time. Exports of German cheese to other EU countries are rising, with the exception of Italy. In the United States, the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan, Romano, and all other types of cheese in the table below continue to be steady compared to last week.

report narrative: In the European Union (EU), the cheese market remained competitive because of lower price levels. Reports suggest that the strong value of the euro against the U.S. dollar does not have much effect on competitiveness. In 2017, cheese was the most exported dairy product in the EU, with an increase in exports of 4 percent compared to 2016. This is mainly the result of increased demand from Japan and Chile. Cheese production in the EU is active as milk supplies are plentiful. Inventories of cheese are currently similar to that of last week. In Germany, stocks are at a normal level for the season. In the United States, the prices for wholesale blue, gorgonzola, parmesan Italy, and Romano are down $.0500 whereas the prices for Swiss cuts Switzerland increased $.0200. All other prices are even compared to the prior week.
commodity narrative: N/A
methodology: Information for the period February 5 - 9, 2018, issued weekly
